<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-214-882  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 214 882.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  April 1989 v18 n5 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>British Rail takes the steam out of a virus. (formation of theComputer Threat Research Association - CoTRA)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mantelman, Lee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Dedicated employees at British Rail successfully vanquish a virusthat invaded one of its over 600 Novell local area networks(LANs).andP;  The employees dealt with the virus without outside help.andO;First, they shut down the infected network.andP;  Second, theyconfiscated all exchangeable media associated with the network andits users.andP;  Then they set up a special room where all virus workwas done.andP;  They used various generally available debugging toolsto discover how the virus worked, which gave them enoughinformation to write a program to tell if the virus was active ina machine and which files were infected.andP;  The final step wasissuing virus checking software to all network nodes.andP;  BritishRail joins with Novell UK, Price Waterhouse, Sophos Ltd andComputer Security Ltd to form the Computer Threat Research Assn(CoTRA) to 'identify, analyze and find solutions to the integrityof computer systems.'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Rail (automation).andO;Topic:     Computer virusesComputer CrimeComputer Threat Research AssociationLocal Area NetworksOrganizationsRailroad Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Viral dos and don'ts. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>